Heads up!

Pause. You are about to encounter something which, though not difficult to grasp, requires that you to focus on it for a hot second, if you’ve never encountered it before. An analogous level of difficulty would be learning how to diagram a sentence. Some people learn this in grade-school, some never encounter the task at all. It’s not “hard” material, and you can be excellent at sentences (writing, reading—the works), and not have the foggiest clue how to diagram one. Basically, it’s something that’s non-obvious, if new.

Frankly, sentence diagramming is slightly more confusing, for my money. For the literate, English-speaking reader, simple sentences are easy to parse (e.g. subject and predicate; interrogative sentences, direct objects).

But reading is different from knowing the rules that govern such a diagram.

What’s more, things get fairly complicated when we examine the types of sentences we tend to actually use in real life (you don’t need to know how to diagram a relative clause or even what one is in order to speak them).

Like, you kow how to read this sentence, but do you know how to break it down into a sentence diagram? I didn’t (hence my adapting it from Pop Chart Lab’s super cool first-line-of-novels-sentence-diagram poster).

How about the opening line from George Orwell’s 1984?

Prefix-ify

Here is a very simple example of “prefixifying,” if we allow (for the moment) that + and sum() are one and the same.

8 + 3
## [1] 11
sum(8, 3)
## [1] 11

Turns out, there’s a way to do this for any infix function, even if you don’t have an equivalent function handy: add backticks ``.

`+`(8, 3)
## [1] 11

OK, let’s mix it up a little bit. What if there are two infix operators?

y <- x * 10

As Shannon Sharpe might say, “that ain’t no problem!”

`<-`(y, `*`(x, 10))

OK, so what about precedence?

The example used in Advanced R is actually quite similar to another grammatical favourite: the Oxford comma.

First, the R example: What does 1 + 2 * 3 yield? Do you get 9 (i.e. (1 + 2) * 3), or 7 (i.e. 1 + (2 * 3))?

For our sentence diagram, we want to know if we have a compound object (consisting of: rhinoceri, Washington, Lincoln), or if Washington and Lincoln are an appositive noun clause.
